From what you are trying to, I am assuming that you are trying to add a force to the object that it has collided with.

First of all, you did:
```
if (myCollision.gameObject.name == &quot;Cube&quot;)
  {
    var = GameObject.Find(&quot;Cube&quot;);
    var.AddForce(new Vector3(0.0f, 0.0f, power));
  }
```

Try to avoid `GameObject.Find(string)` method, as it is an expensive call.&lt;br&gt;
In fact, you don&#39;t even need to do that, since you actually have the game object you are colliding with already, that is what the `myCollision` for.

You can do this instead:
```
if (myCollision.gameObject.name == &quot;Cube&quot;)
  {
    var = myCollision.gameObject; // Aka the gameobject you have collided with.
    var.AddForce(new Vector3(0.0f, 0.0f, power));
  }
```

**Going back to the question**, what you were trying to do is to add force to a rigidbody, but however `var` is of type `GameObject`, not `RigidBody`.

What you need to do is to get the component of the `RigidBody` from the `GameObject`, like so:

```
var.GetComponent&lt;Rigidbody&gt;().AddForce(...
```
Note that a null reference exception occurs if the GameObject does not have a Rigidbody component attached to it.&lt;br&gt;
Make sure the cube you are colliding with has a RigidBody component in the Unity&#39;s Inspector.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Also, you might want to note that repeated `GetComponent()` calls can be expensive. You can consider caching it if possible.

